knowledge_graph.title: Cardoon
knowledge_graph.description: The cardoon, also called the artichoke thistle, is a thistle in the family Asteraceae. It is a naturally occurring species that also has many cultivated forms, including the globe artichoke. It is native to the Mediterranean region, where it was domesticated in ancient times and still occurs as a wild plant.

related_questions.question: What's the difference between an artichoke and a cardoon?
related_questions.snippet: A close cousin of the artichoke is a plant called a cardoon (Cynara cardunculus). The cardoon is actually the wild form of the cultivated artichoke. It is grown not for its edible flower but for its edible stalk. The cardoon is much more cold tolerant as well.
